# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The 1882 season was the first for the **Alleghenys**, later known as the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] They finished at exactly a .500 record, 39 wins and 39 losses, good for fourth place in the new American Association.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The team played its home games in Allegheny City, across the Allegheny River from Pittsburgh.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] Chartered as the Allegheny Base Ball Club of Pittsburgh, the team appeared as "Allegheny" in the standings and was often referred to in the plural as the Alleghenys.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The club was not related to the earlier Alleghenys of the International Association.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1883-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The **1883 Pittsburgh Alleghenys season** was the second season of the Pittsburgh Alleghenys franchise.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1883-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The Alleghenys finished seventh in the American Association with a record of 31–67.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1884-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The **1884 Pittsburgh Alleghenys season** was the third season of the Pittsburgh Alleghenys franchise.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1884-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The Alleghenys finished 11th in the American Association with a record of 30–78.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1885-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The **1885 Pittsburgh Alleghenys season** was the fourth season of the Pittsburgh Alleghenys franchise.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1885-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The Alleghenys finished third in the American Association with a record of 56–55.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1886-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The **1886 Pittsburgh Alleghenys season** was the fifth season of the Pittsburgh Alleghenys franchise.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1886-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The Alleghenys finished second in the American Association with a record of 80–57.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1887-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The **1887 Pittsburgh Alleghenys season** was the sixth season of the Pittsburgh Alleghenys franchise and its first in the National League, where they remain to this day.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1887-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The Alleghenys finished sixth in the standings with a record of 55–69.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1894 Pittsburgh Pirates season** was the 13th season of the Pittsburgh Pirates franchise; their eighth in the National League.
[src:1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1894-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates finished seventh in the National League with a record of 65–65.
